com.flowpowered.commands

Class CommandArguments

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.flowpowered.commands.CommandArguments
  • Direct Known Subclasses:
    PositionallyOverridableCommandArguments

    public class CommandArguments
extends Object
    This class is used as a wrapper for command arguments to make them easily parse-able. Please note that the javadocs for the pop* methods describe how input is currently handled. Handling may change over time, and while efforts are made to retain backwards compatibility it is not always possible.

      • hasNext

        public boolean hasNext(String argName)
        Returns whether calling currentArgument(argName) would have any argument to return.

        Returns true when there's some more unparsed arguments, or the argument with specified name is overriden. If it returns false then calling currentArgument(String) with the same argName would result in an exception due to argument not being present.

        Parameters:

        Returns:

        public InvalidCommandArgumentException failure(String argName,

        Called when an error has occurred while parsing the specified argument due to the argument being invalid Example: 
           if (success) {
       return success(argName, myValue);
     } else {
       throw failure(argName, "I dun goofed", false);
     }
        Parameters:
        argName - The name of the argument
        error - The error that occurred
        silenceable - Whether the error can be silenced by using the default value for the argument
        Returns:
        The exception -- must be thrown

      • currentArgument

        public String currentArgument(String argName)
                       throws InvalidCommandArgumentException
        Return the current argument, without advancing the argument index. Combines quoted strings provided as arguments as necessary. If there are no arguments remaining, the default value is returned.
        Parameters:
        argName - The name of the argument
        Returns:
        The argument with the current index.
        Throws:
        InvalidCommandArgumentException - if an invalid quoted string was attempted to be used
        See Also:
        success(String, Object), #failure(String, String, boolean, String...), for getting a string-typed argument
